<span id="freeTextContainer9118896500626100253">I&apos;ve read this collection of short stories several times. I would love to live in one of Rosamunde Pilcher&apos;s Scottish or Cornish villages. The stories explore universal themes like love and marriage, friendship, birth, death, and dreams coming true. She writes about all types of characters, children, young women, bachelors, newlyweds, older gentlemen and mothers and fathers. All of the characters are likeable and full of life. My favorite story is &quot;The Blackberry Day.&quot; Claudia, who has been enta</span>
  <span id="freeText9118896500626100253" style="display:none">I've read this collection of short stories several times. I would love to live in one of Rosamunde Pilcher's Scottish or Cornish villages. The stories explore universal themes like love and marriage, friendship, birth, death, and dreams coming true. She writes about all types of characters, children, young women, bachelors, newlyweds, older gentlemen and mothers and fathers. All of the characters are likeable and full of life. My favorite story is "The Blackberry Day." Claudia, who has been entangled with the elusive Giles for years, retreats to the Scottish highlands after he cancels their planned vacation to Spain. Returning to the village where she spent many happy childhood summers, she reevaluates her love life and reconnects with a charming bachelor she had known as a young girl.</span>
